<HEADLINE>
<P>
'TRADITION' AND THE WORKING WOMAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For the last two decades, women have been striving to earn their due 
recognition as individuals -- equal partners with men in the home and 
workplace. While this change has created anxiety in many women and threatened 
many men, the net result has given all of us greater options in how we choose 
to live our lives. 
</P>
<P>
I am discouraged by the recent trend in politics and advertising that professes 
a return to the "traditional values." As a single parent, I value the unique 
strength a family can provide, regardless of the form it takes. 
</P>
<P>
Each family must be created by individuals willing to give equally in a manner 
that best suits its circumstance. The "life style" professed by the Good 
Housekeeping ad campaign dictates a stereotype that can only create unnecessary 
anxiety and frustration for women, and men, too. 
</P>
<P>
Parents and children must create their own roles in the changing family and not 
give in to the simplistic wishes of the advertising industry. Change can be 
positive when viewed as an opportunity rather than a threat. 
</P>
<P>
RICHARD ALAN HALES 
</P>
<P>
Laguna Hills 
</P>
