<HEADLINE>
<P>
TRAVELER'S DIARY: A MOVABLE FEAST MOVES FROM PARIS AREA TO PAU 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By HORACE SUTTON, Sutton is a New York City syndicated travel columnist. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
EUGENIE-LES-BAINS, France 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the early '70s, a diminutive and somewhat rotund chef named Michel Guerard 
won three Michelin stars for his tiny restaurant on a back-of-the-lot fringe of 
Paris. 
</P>
<P>
It was called Pot au Feu, and serious and famous eaters flocked there until 
Paris, in its infinite wisdom, decided a new roadway was needed. Alas, it was 
placed right in the path of Guerard's tiny temple. The fire went out at Pot au 
Feu, but it burned even brighter in Guerard's belly. 
</P>
<P>
Michel and his wife Christine picked up the pieces and moved to the vicinity of 
Pau, southeast of Bordeaux and east of Biarritz, where royalty used to play, a 
whistle away from the Spanish border. 
</P>
<P>
Christine's family had property in the middle of a wide area of thermal springs 
first developed by Henri IV. She and Michel settled in the town called 
Eugenie-les-Bains, so named because Empress Eugenie, wife of Napoleon III, came 
here to bathe in the natural hot springs. 
</P>
<P>
Together they built a small but elegant hotel that shelters 35 guests (eight 
more rooms are being built). Each room was given a name that would summon a 
dream -- buttercup, citronella, rosewood, clouds. Some faced the magnolias, 
palms, bamboo, tulips, water lilies, orange trees and banana trees. Others 
faced the pool set in a meadow sprinkled with peonies and iris. 
</P>
<P>
There are tennis courts for the hyperactive, petanque for those who want to 
roll a ball down an alleyway, and billiards for inclement days. There isn't a 
room deodorant spray can in sight; bundles of fresh rosemary hang in the room 
closets, tied with white ribbons. 
</P>
<P>
While the spa was developed, Michel created Cuisine Minceur, a cuisine of 
slimness, and even wrote a book about it. He confessed that he had been a chef 
gourmand who liked his robust food. But Christine, who would soon marry him, 
whispered in his ear: "You know, Michel, if you would lose some weight you 
would look great." 
</P>
<P>
Those few words created a whole new enterprise. And from Michel's new kitchen 
in the South of France there came a whole new way to eat elegantly while 
sidestepping calories. A sample menu might include lobster salad with mangoes, 
roast pigeon with spicy mincemeat, crepes filled with apples and a lemony 
apricot mousse. 
</P>
<P>
To be sure, a chef of his talents couldn't avoid producing, at the same time, a 
carte gourmande -- golden pates, a "pillow" of mushrooms and truffles in cream, 
fat disks of foie gras from Landes (some say the best in France), oven-roasted 
salmon perfumed with truffle oil, pastry fritters stuffed with crayfish and an 
artichoke salad swimming in olive oil, plus pig's feet and mashed potatoes with 
truffles, rabbit and chopped bits of goose with sweetbreads. 
</P>
<P>
Of course, one could end the horn of plenty with iced fruit and sherbet 
spilling out or go the whole cochon (hog) with the dessert du roi, the dessert 
of the king -- all in chocolate, including a hot souffle, chocolate ices and a 
pot de creme. 
</P>
<P>
Even for those who eat at the Cuisine Minceur and are laved by the waters, 
Michel and Christine suggest having one last meal chosen from the gourmand 
menu. You will have earned it after you've tubbed in hot spa water, been 
sprayed with a hose and taken an underwater massage where a masseuse works over 
your belly. 
</P>
<P>
For some (though not for me), a white mud bath is sheer weightless heaven; 
weightless because you seem to float in white goo. And after radio evaporation, 
a tingling high-pressure needle shower and a swallow or two of diuretic water, 
there is, for ladies anyway, the beauty parlor. 
</P>
<P>
During the stay, whether in the spa or not, one is encouraged to drink mint and 
chamomile tea and to inhale the verbena, sweet basil, chives and sage that 
perfume the air. You can walk a boulevard lined with rosemary to the fussy 
little church that stands at the crossroads at the very entranceway to Michel 
and Christine's corner of heaven. 
</P>
<P>
The success of Les Pres d'Eugenie would have satisfied most kitchen creators, 
but not Michel. He spent seven months at wine school and bought the Chateau 
Bachen estate a few miles from Eugenie-les-Bains. Here he is growing four kinds 
of grapes that he will begin to market this year under the label of the Baron 
de Bachen. They will be bottled in elongated flasks that resemble tall bottles 
of Bordeaux, a region which is, after all, a neighbor. 
</P>
<P>
It is a white wine fruity with suspicions of cumin and thyme to tease the 
palate. In the middle of the wine field sits the Baron's old 17th-Century 
chateau, which Michel and Christine have redone in splendid style, with a big 
kitchen range that Christine designed (and sells to other restaurants and large 
houses), and even an octagonal porcelain hot tub. This is where they live. 
</P>
<P>
Besides all that, the Guerards are about to produce an armagnac, a cousin of 
cognac being distilled at another chateau 45 minutes away. What else? Well, 
Michel has given up Bloomingdale's, where he maintained a fine food station for 
awhile. 
</P>
<P>
He still creates frozen foods in France, Switzerland and Belgium, an outgrowth 
of his work with Stouffer's, which produces Lean Cuisine -- an idea he 
developed with Stouffer's parent company, Nestle. 
</P>
<P>
In the center of the vineyard, below the grand building where the grapes will 
be pressed, barreled, aged and bottled, a tiered amphitheater is taking shape. 
</P>
<P>
Summer musical festivals will be held there. Michel Guerard -- wine maker, 
armagnac distiller, creator of Cuisine Minceur and Cuisine Gourmande -- might 
very well do a turn on stage himself. 
</P>
<P>
"I may sing," he says. He surely has plenty to sing about. 
</P>
<P>
 -- -- -- 
</P>
<P>
Les Pres d'Eugenie hotel and restaurant, 40320 Geaune, France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Les Pres d'Eugenie hotel features cuisine of Michel Guerard. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
