<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST GERMANY PLANS MAJOR EXPANSION OF NUCLEAR POWER-PRODUCING PLANTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
EAST BERLIN 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
East Germany will greatly increase its nuclear power capacity over the next 
decade, an official East Berlin newspaper said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
The Berliner Zeitung said the government was aiming for a capacity of between 
6,000 and 7,000 megawatts by the year 2000. 
</P>
<P>
Five of eight planned 400-megawatt reactors were on line in the northern city 
of Greifswald, with a 1,000-megawatt unit due to open this year, it said. 
</P>
<P>
An unspecified number were operating in the central towns of Stendal and 
Rheinsberg. 
</P>
<P>
Ten percent of East Germany's electricity is derived from nuclear power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
