<HEADLINE>
<P>
JAIL TIME, FINES SOUGHT FOR REPORTERS ACCUSED OF DEFYING JUDGE'S GAG ORDER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By AP 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WHEATON, Ill. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Prosecutors said they will seek fines and jail time for two Chicago Tribune 
reporters accused of defying a judge's gag order in publishing the name of a 
boy accused of stabbing three classmates. 
</P>
<P>
Circuit Judge Robert E. Byrne, who issued the gag order, declined to drop 
contempt of court charges against reporters Joseph Sjostrom and Jan Crawford 
during a hearing last week but said he would give the case to another judge. 
</P>
<P>
Assistant state's Atty. Carmen Polo said he would seek fines and jail sentences 
if the two are convicted. 
</P>
<P>
Byrne had ordered news media not to identify the 14-year-old charged in the 
stabbings at a high school Dec. 7. The Tribune had published the teen's name 
before the judge issued the order and published it again the day after the 
order. 
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said the reporters had obtained the boy's name after interviewing 
his mother and students at the school in Elmhurst. 
</P>
<P>
"Truthful information in the public domain can't be made secret again by an 
order," said Joseph P. Thornton, an attorney for the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
