</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cambodians marked the 10th anniversary of the end of brutal Khmer Rouge rule, 
and the head of the Vietnamese-supported government in Phnom Penh said there 
will be no going back. The Cambodian revolution "is absolutely irreversible," 
President Heng Samrin said in a speech. More than a million Cambodians died 
during the 1975-78 Khmer Rouge rule that ended with a Vietnamese invasion in 
late 1978 and installation of a new regime in Cambodia on Jan. 7, 1979. Vietnam 
has promised to withdraw its troops by 1990, and Cambodian officials announced 
last week that the troops would leave by next September if a political 
settlement is reached. 
</P>
