<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO SPORTS ET CETERA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CURT HOLBREICH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Darrin Wagner, the 1987 Times' All-San Diego County running back from Lincoln 
High School, said he will transfer from San Diego State to Nebraska. 
</P>
<P>
Wagner said he will leave Thursday for Lincoln, Neb., and enroll for the spring 
semester beginning Jan. 16. 
</P>
<P>
Wagner, a 6-foot 190-pounder, did not play in a game for the Aztecs as a 
freshman. Under NCAA rules, he must sit out the 1989 season and will have three 
seasons of football eligibility remaining. CURT HOLBREICH 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA010889-0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 2814 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 8, 1989, Sunday, San Diego County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part 3; Page 11B; Column 2; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
333 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO SPORTS ET CETERA: BADMINTON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Four nationally ranked players will take to the courts today in the finals of 
the third annual San Diego Open Badminton Tournament at 10 a.m. at the Federal 
Building in Balboa Park. 
</P>
<P>
Joy Kitzmiller (Manhattan Beach), the No. 1 U.S. women's singles player, will 
play Canada's Denyse Jullien in one final. 
</P>
<P>
The No. 1 U.S. men's doubles team of Chris Jogis (Redondo Beach) and Benny Lee 
(Tempe, Ariz.) will play Mike Walker and Fredrico Valdez (Peru). Jogis, ranked 
No. 1 in men's singles, will then play Lee. 
</P>
<P>
WOMEN'S BASKETBALL 
</P>
<P>
Point Loma Nazarene won the Whittier tournament with a 72-37 victory over UC 
Santa Cruz. Camille Armijo led Point Loma (9-4) with 16. Ann Duffy, the 
tournament MVP, and Shawndel Reddic added 12 each. 
</P>
<P>
The University of San Diego (4-6) broke a 3-game losing streak by defeating 
Weber State (7-2), 78-74, in Ogden Utah. USD's Molly Hunter made two free 
throws with 23 seconds left to clinch it. 
</P>
<P>
San Diego State remained undefeated (12-0) by defeating host UC Santa Barbara 
(4-8), 91-61. SDSU was led by Chana Perry with 33 points and 12 rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
BASEBALL 
</P>
<P>
The San Diego Stars all-star team returned Friday from Australia, where it won 
the 1988-89 Australian International Boys' Baseball Tournament. The Stars, made 
up of 11- and 12-year-olds, finished 8-0 and won the championship with a 2-0 
victory over the Australian national team from Sydney. University City's Travis 
Ahern, the tournament MVP, threw a 6-inning 2-hitter in the final game for his 
second victory. 
</P>
<P>
MEN'S BASKETBALL 
</P>
<P>
Point Loma Nazarene lost to Trevecca Nazarene, 118-80, in the third-place game 
of the Point Loma Tournament. David Shelton led Trevecca (7-9) with 30 points; 
Mark Ryan led Point Loma (2-11) with 22. Biola defeated Olivet Nazarene, 86-61, 
for the championship. 
</P>
<P>
UC San Diego lost to Millikin (7-2), 75-70, in the championship round of the La 
Jolla Classic. UCSD (4-8) was led by Kirk Kramer (20), Rick Batt (12), and Bill 
Gerlach (9), who were all named to the all-tournament team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Game Story 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA010889-0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 2821 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 8, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
