Opinion; Part 5; Page 4; Column 5; Letters Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
37 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTH AFRICA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Regarding the article "S. Africa -- A Champion for Wildlife," (Part I, Dec. 
30): Isn't it sad that the South Africans take better care of their wildlife 
population than their human population? 
</P>
<P>
LISA VITIELLO 
</P>
<P>
San Diego 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA010889-0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 2974 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 8, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Opinion; Part 5; Page 4; Column 6; Letters Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
80 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
TURNING AWAY THE HOMELESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I cannot believe that suffering needs proper English or Spanish to be 
understood or attended to. Such response on the part of charitable services is 
unconscionable. 
</P>
<P>
Further, I cannot understand why we continue to pretend that a working 
knowledge of Spanish isn't necessary for life in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
Perhaps, if some status points were applied to the speaking of Spanish, being 
bilingual would be as popular among the upwardly mobile as driving a BMW. 
</P>
<P>
LOIS DRAKE 
</P>
<P>
Hermosa Beach 
</P>
</TEXT>
