<HEADLINE>
<P>
'YELLOWSTONE' THE NOVEL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I am disappointed in Michael J. Carroll's review (Book Review, Nov. 20) of my 
novel, "The Yellowstone." 
</P>
<P>
Carroll doesn't take care of the first piece of business of any review, to 
report to the reader the basic facts about the book. So here they are. 
</P>
<P>
 "The Yellowstone": The first of a series called Rivers West, is a generational 
novel set in the Yellowstone country about the trader Mac Maclean and his 
family of Indian wives and half-breed children. In the first part, at the end 
of the fur trade era, Mac tries to establish a life for himself among the 
Cheyennes. A generation later, the family struggles to keep its native life way 
in the face of the Montana gold rush. The book has a bizarre cast, from 
idiosyncratic mountain men to a Scots lord to a Cheyenne male who lives his 
life as a female to a Jewish peddler, of all things, who traipses the Great 
Plains pulling a handcart full of sewing gear. 
</P>
<P>
Aside from underreporting, Carroll does some misreporting: He invents a rape 
that isn't there, and calls my book a frontier novel when it's set a thousand 
miles beyond the frontier. He also chastises me for my descriptions of the 
Yellowstone country. But those descriptions are from the point of view of the 
central character, Mac, so the language is not mine but his. 
</P>
<P>
I'll grant Carroll whatever opinion of my novel he likes, but not his critical 
ineptitude. If I'm going to get knocked, I want to get knocked by somebody 
good. 
</P>
<P>
WINFRED BLEVINS 
</P>
<P>
JACKSON, WYO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
